15.3 Interrupt-Driven Approach
15.3.1 What is an Interrupt?
An interrupt is a signal that immediately stops the CPU’s current task and forces it
to execute a specific function (Interrupt Service Routine- ISR). Once the ISR completes,
the CPU resumes its previous task.
15.3.2 Advantages of Interrupts
• Efficient: CPUisnot constantly checking input; it runs other tasks and only reacts
when needed.
• Responsive: Immediate response to events.
